Cloud properties are added for configuration of federated regions (clouds):

* region.region_configuration
* region.region_name

The first property is for a JSON document that will be the same for all federated regions. The second property identifies the local region.

An example configuration document is:

{code}
{
    "Regions": [
        {
            "Name": "region-1",
            "CertificateFingerprintDigest": "SHA-256",
            "CertificateFingerprint": "EC:E7:3D:DF:97:43:00:9E:FC:F0:2C:6D:98:D2:82:EB:AA:04:75:10:E7:C2:F2:6F:31:F1:F1:CA:A1:61:DE:41",
            "IdentifierPartitions": [
                10
            ],
            "Services": [
                {
                    "Type": "identity",
                    "Endpoints": [
                        "https://eucalyptus.one.example.com:8773/services/Identity"
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}
{code}

The example shows a single region, typically there would be multiple regions in the "Regions" list. The region name is required and should be valid for use in a DNS name. The certificate fingerprint references the Eucalyptus certificate and the default digest is SHA-256. You can calculate a fingerprint from the certificate using OpenSSL when the PEM file is available:

{code}
openssl x509 -inform PEM -in cloud-cert.pem -noout -fingerprint -sha256
{code}

alternatively you may be able to grab via SSL:

{code}
openssl s_client -showcerts -connect 10.111.1.22:8773 < /dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -noout -fingerprint -sha256
{code}

The identifier partitions must include at least one value in the 1-999 range, these values must be different for each region.

The services for each region must include an "identity" service with an HTTPS endpoint.

When the configuration is updated, it is expected that up to a minute wait is required before access keys from newly added regions can be used.

